      <h2>The Seven Swaras</h2>
      <p>Indian classical music uses seven fundamental notes called swaras. Their full Sanskrit names are Shadja (Sa), Rishabh (Re), Gandhar (Ga), Madhyama (Ma), Pancham (Pa), Dhaivat (Dha), and Nishad (Ni). These correspond to Western notes C D E F G A B. The cycle repeats — after Ni comes Sa again one octave higher. This repeating 7-note cycle is called a Saptak.</p>

      <h2>Komal and Tivra</h2>
      <p>Beyond the 7 natural swaras Indian music uses 5 more altered notes making 12 total. Four swaras can be komal (flattened): Komal Re (C#), Komal Ga (D#), Komal Dha (G#), Komal Ni (A#). Only one swara can be tivra (sharpened): Tivra Ma (F#). Sa and Pa are achala (fixed) — they never change. Different ragas use different combinations of these 12 notes.</p>

      <h2>Sargam Notation Symbols</h2>
      <p>Natural swaras are written as capital letters: S R G M P D N. Komal swaras are written lowercase or with underline: r g d n. Tivra Ma is written M' or M with accent. Lower octave (Mandra) gets a dot below the letter. Upper octave (Taar) gets a dot above. Spaces between letters indicate separate beats. A vertical line separates taal sections.</p>

      <h2>Importance of Sa as Anchor</h2>
      <p>Unlike Western music where C is always C, in Indian music Sa can be any pitch comfortable for the singer. All other swaras are defined relative to Sa. This relative quality makes Indian music flexible and voice-centered. On harmonium we typically use C as Sa for learning — but a scale-changer harmonium allows shifting Sa to any position.</p>

      <h2>Reading Notation Practice</h2>
      <p>Practice reading these notations: Ascending scale S R G M P D N S. Yaman aroha N R G M' P D N upper-S. Bhairavi aroha S r g M P d n upper-S. Yaman pakad N R G comma M' G R S. Read each notation aloud before playing it. This simultaneous reading and playing builds musical literacy quickly.</p>

